Prior predictive checks with R (without Stan).

prev <- rbeta(n=1e5, shape1=1, shape2=1)
Se   <- rbeta(n=1e5, shape1=1, shape2=1)
Sp   <- rbeta(n=1e5, shape1=1, shape2=1)
pos_test_rate <- prev * Se + (1-prev) * (1-Sp)

pos_test_rate %>% as_tibble() %>% 
  ggplot(.) + geom_density(aes(x=value)) + theme_bw() + xlab("Prior predictive positive test rate") + scale_x_continuous(limits=c(0,1))

prev <- rbeta(n=1e5, shape1=1, shape2=1)
Se   <- rbeta(n=1e5, shape1=10, shape2=2)
Sp   <- rbeta(n=1e5, shape1=10, shape2=2)
pos_test_rate <- prev * Se + (1-prev) * (1-Sp)

Prior predictive checks in R with bivariate normal prior

library(mvtnorm)
inv_logit <- function(x) exp(x)/(1+exp(x))
logit_Se_Sp <- rmvnorm(n=1e5, mean=c(1.84, 1.81), sigma=matrix(c(0.37, -0.07, -0.07, 0.77), nrow=2, byrow=TRUE))
Se <- inv_logit(logit_Se_Sp[,1]) 
Sp <- inv_logit(logit_Se_Sp[,2])

prev <- rbeta(n=1e5, shape1=1, shape2=1)
pos_test_rate <- prev * Se + (1-prev) * (1-Sp)

pos_test_rate %>% as_tibble() %>% 
  ggplot(.) + geom_density(aes(x=value)) + theme_bw() + xlab("Prior predictive positive test rate") + scale_x_continuous(limits=c(0,1))

Basic stan model to estimate the prevalence:

prevalence_model1 <- stan_model("prevalence_model_practise.stan")
prevalence_model1 %>% print()
## S4 class stanmodel 'prevalence_model_practise' coded as follows:
## data {
##   int<lower = 0> n; // number of tested persons
##   int<lower = 0> y; // number of positive persons
##   vector<lower = 0>[2] beta_prev;
##   vector<lower = 0>[2] beta_sens;
##   vector<lower = 0>[2] beta_spec;
## }
## parameters {
##   real<lower = 0, upper = 1> prev;
##   real<lower = 0, upper = 1> sens;
##   real<lower = 0, upper = 1> spec;
## }
## transformed parameters {
##   real<lower = 0, upper = 1> p;
##   p = prev * sens + (1 - prev) * (1 - spec);
## }
## model {
##   y ~ binomial(n, p);
##   prev ~ beta(beta_prev[1],beta_prev[2]);
##   sens ~ beta(beta_sens[1],beta_sens[2]);
##   spec ~ beta(beta_spec[1],beta_spec[2]);
## }
## 
## generated quantities {
##   int y_pred = binomial_rng(n, p);
## }

We receive several warning messages by Stan. Additionally, the trace plot of the chains do not look very good, indicating poor convergence.

One (of several) option is to set higher values for adapt_delta and max_treedepth, basically increasing the computational complexity of the mcmc sampling and (ideally) increasing reliability of the posterior samples (at the cost of larger computation time).

fit <- sampling(prevalence_model1, data=stan_data, chains=4, iter=2000, refresh=0, control=list(adapt_delta=0.95, max_treedepth=15), cores=1)
## Warning: There were 5 divergent transitions after warmup. See
## https://mc-stan.org/misc/warnings.html#divergent-transitions-after-warmup
## to find out why this is a problem and how to eliminate them.
## Warning: Examine the pairs() plot to diagnose sampling problems
mcmc_trace(fit)

We mya still receive a warning about (few) divergent transitions. This is acceptable if there are not too many, and a consequence of the quite weakly informative priors, particularly for the prevalence. You can try out more informative priors, e.g.Beta(2,10), and there should be no more warnings.

Prior predictive checks with stan

prior_predictive_model <- stan_model("prior_predictive_model_HARMONY.stan")

stan_data <- list(n=24404, y=2269, mu=c(1.84,1.81), Sigma=matrix(c(0.77,-0.07,-0.07,0.37), nrow=2), prev_beta=c(1,1))

fit_prior_pred <- sampling(prior_predictive_model, data=stan_data[names(stan_data) != "y"], chains=4, iter=10000, refresh=0)
prior_pred_cases_1 <- rstan::extract(fit_prior_pred, "y_pred")[[1]]

data.frame(pos_test_rate = prior_pred_cases_1/stan_data$n) %>% 
  ggplot(.) + geom_density(aes(x=pos_test_rate)) +
  scale_x_continuous("Positive test rate in %", labels = function(x) sprintf("%.0f", x*100), limits=c(0,1)) + 
  scale_y_continuous("Density", breaks = NULL) +
  theme_bw()

stan_data[["prev_beta"]] <- c(1.5,11)

fit_prior_pred <- sampling(prior_predictive_model, data=stan_data[names(stan_data) != "y"], chains=4, iter=10000, refresh=0)
prior_pred_cases <- rstan::extract(fit_prior_pred, "y_pred")[[1]]

data.frame(pos_test_rate = prior_pred_cases/stan_data$n) %>% 
  ggplot(.) + geom_density(aes(x=pos_test_rate)) +
  scale_x_continuous("Positive test rate in %", labels = function(x) sprintf("%.0f", x*100), limits=c(0,1)) + 
  scale_y_continuous("Density", breaks = NULL) +
  theme_bw()

stan_data[["mu"]] <- c(1.81,3)

fit_prior_pred <- sampling(prior_predictive_model, data=stan_data[names(stan_data) != "y"], chains=4, iter=10000, refresh=0)
prior_pred_cases <- rstan::extract(fit_prior_pred, "y_pred")[[1]]

data.frame(pos_test_rate = prior_pred_cases/stan_data$n) %>% 
  ggplot(.) + geom_density(aes(x=pos_test_rate)) +
  scale_x_continuous("Positive test rate in %", labels = function(x) sprintf("%.0f", x*100), limits=c(0,1)) +

Run a prior sensitivity analysis.

library(posterior)
library(tibble)
library(tidyr)

stan_data <- list(n=24404, y=2269, mu=c(1.84,1.81), Sigma=matrix(c(0.77,-0.07,-0.07,0.37), nrow=2), prev_beta=c(1,1))
fit1 <- sampling(bivariate_normal_model, data=stan_data, chains=4, iter=10000, refresh=0, control=list(adapt_delta=0.95, max_treedepth=15))
posterior_prev1 <- rstan::extract(fit1, "prev")[[1]]  %>% as_tibble()

stan_data[["prev_beta"]] <- c(1.5,11)
fit2 <- sampling(bivariate_normal_model, data=stan_data, chains=4, iter=10000, refresh=0, control=list(adapt_delta=0.95, max_treedepth=15))
posterior_prev2 <- rstan::extract(fit2, "prev")[[1]]  %>% as_tibble()

stan_data[["mu"]] <- c(1.81,3)
fit3 <- sampling(bivariate_normal_model, data=stan_data, chains=4, iter=10000, refresh=0, control=list(adapt_delta=0.95, max_treedepth=15))
posterior_prev3 <- rstan::extract(fit3, "prev")[[1]]  %>% as_tibble()

plotdat <- bind_rows(
  as_draws_df(fit1) %>% select(starts_with("prev")) %>% add_column("prior_specification"="Main analysis"),
  as_draws_df(fit2) %>% select(starts_with("prev")) %>% add_column("prior_specification"="Informative prior on prevalence"),
  as_draws_df(fit3) %>% select(starts_with("prev")) %>% add_column("prior_specification"="Informative prior on prevalence\nand adjusted specificity")) %>%
  group_by(prior_specification) %>% 
  summarise(m = median(prev), lo = quantile(prev, probs = .025), hi = quantile(prev, probs = .975), lo2 = quantile(prev, probs = .25), hi2 = quantile(prev, probs = .75))
## Warning: Dropping 'draws_df' class as required metadata was removed.

## Warning: Dropping 'draws_df' class as required metadata was removed.

## Warning: Dropping 'draws_df' class as required metadata was removed.
plotdat$prior_specification = factor(plotdat$prior_specification, 
                                     levels = c("Main analysis", "Informative prior on prevalence", "Informative prior on prevalence\nand adjusted specificity"))


ggplot(plotdat, aes(y = m, x=prior_specification, col = prior_specification)) + 
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = lo, ymax = hi), position = position_dodge(width = -0.7), width = .1) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = lo2, ymax = hi2), position = position_dodge(width = -0.7), width = .1, size = 1.2) +
  geom_point(aes(shape = prior_specification), fill = "white", position = position_dodge(width = -0.7), size = 2) + 
  theme_bw() + theme(legend.position = "bottom", panel.grid.major.y=element_blank(), panel.grid.minor.y=element_blank()) + 
  coord_flip() +
  scale_shape_manual("Prior specification", values = c(21:23)) +
  scale_color_brewer("Prior specification", type = "qual", palette = 6) +
  scale_y_continuous("Prevalence", breaks = seq(0,.15,.025), labels = function(x) paste0(sprintf("%.1f", x*100), "%")) + 
  scale_x_discrete("Country") + geom_hline(yintercept = stan_data$y/stan_data$n, linetype="dashed")
